<worksheet xml:id="activities-funcs">

<activity>
	<p>
	Suppose <m>n</m> is a fixed but unknown positive integer,
	and let <m>\funcdef{D}{\R}{\R^n}</m> represent the function defined by <m>D(x) = (x,x,\dotsc,x)</m>.
	</p><p>
	Write a set definition in <xref ref="subsection-sets-defining-candidate-condition" text="title" /> for the image set <m>D(\R)</m>.
	Then do the same for the graph <m>\funcgraph{D}</m>.
	</p>
</activity>

<activity>
	<task><p> Devise an example of a function <m>\N \to \N</m> that is bijective. </p></task>
	<task><p> Devise an example of a function <m>\N \to \N</m> that is injective but not surjective. </p></task>
	<task><p> Devise an example of a function <m>\N \to \N</m> that is surjective but not injective. </p></task>
	<conclusion><p>
		Note that when you define a function, you don't necessarily have to give an input-output <em>formula</em> <mdash />
		you can also use a table of input-output values or just a description in words (<ie /> an <term>algorithm</term>) of how an output is to be produced from an input.
	</p></conclusion>
</activity>

<activity>
	<introduction><p>
		For each function defined below:
		<ol marker="(i)">
			<li>
				Decide whether the function is injective.
				Use the <xref ref="test-funcs-inj" text="custom">Injective Function Test</xref>
				to verify your answer.
			</li>
			<!-- <li>  TODO NEED BETTER EXAMPLES OF DOING THIS
				Determine some pattern that all elements of the image <m>f(B)</m> have in common.
				That is, if you were handed an arbitrary element of the codomain <m>B</m>,
				describe what property or properties you would use to determine whether it was in the subset <m>f(A) \subseteq B</m>.
			</li> -->
			<li>
				Decide whether the function is surjective.
				Use the <xref ref="test-funcs-surj" text="custom">Surjective Function Test</xref>
				to verify your answer.
			</li>
		</ol>
	</p></introduction>
	<task><p>
		<m>\Sigma = \{0,1\}</m>,
		<m>\funcdef{c}{\words{\Sigma}}{\words{\Sigma}}</m> is the <term>bitwise complement</term> function:
		for input word <m>w</m>, the output word <m>c(w)</m> is the word of the same length as <m>w</m> but with a <m>0</m> at every position that <m>w</m> has a <m>1</m>, and a <m>1</m> at every position that <m>w</m> has a <m>0</m>.
	</p></task>
	<task><p> <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R \times \R}</m>,  <m>f(x) = (x+1,x-1)</m>. </p></task>
	<task><p>
		<m>A = \powset{\N} \relcmplmnt \{\emptyset\}</m>,
		<m>\funcdef{m}{A}{\N}</m>,
		<m>m(X) = </m> the smallest number in <m>X</m>.
	</p></task>
</activity>

<activity>
	<p>
	Consider <m>\Sigma = \{0,1\}</m>,
	and recall that for <m>n \in \N</m>, <m>\words{\Sigma}_n</m> is the subset of <m>\words{\Sigma}</m> consisting of all words from the alphabet <m>\Sigma</m> with length <m>n</m>.
	Suppose <m>A = \{a_1,a_2,\dotsc,a_n\}</m> is a set with <m>n</m> distinct elements.
	Construct a bijection <m>\powset{A} \to \words{\Sigma}_n</m>.
	</p><p>
	When attempting this activity,
	remember that when you define a function you don't necessarily have to give an input-output <em>formula</em> <mdash />
	you can also use a description in words (<ie /> an <term>algorithm</term>) of how an output is to be produced from an input.
	</p>
</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-funcs-bij-from-restricted-codomain">
	<introduction><p>
		Suppose <m>A</m> is a set that definitely does not contain any cats,
		and let <md> \funcdef{f}{\powset{A}}{\powset{A \union \{\text{Grumpy Cat}\}}} </md>
		represent the function defined by <md> f(X) = X \union \{\text{Grumpy Cat}\} </md>.
	</p></introduction>
	<task><p> Verify that <m>f</m> is injective. </p></task>
	<task><p> Verify that <m>f</m> is <em>not</em> surjective. </p></task>
	<task xml:id="activity-funcs-bij-from-restricted-codomain-restrict"><p>
		Describe specifically how to make <m>f</m> bijective by <term><xref ref="definition-funcs-restrict-codomain" text="title" /></term>.
	</p></task>
	<task><p>
		As all bijective functions are invertible,
		the bijective version of <m>f</m> from
		<xref ref="activity-funcs-bij-from-restricted-codomain-restrict" text="type-local" />
		has an inverse <m>\inv{f}</m>.
		Describe this inverse by specifying its
		<ol marker="(i)">
			<li> <xref ref="definition-funcs-domain" text="title" />, </li>
			<li> <xref ref="definition-funcs-codomain" text="title" />, and </li>
			<li> <xref ref="definition-funcs-rule" text="title" />. </li>
		</ol>
	</p></task>
</activity>

<activity>
	<introduction><p>
		Let <m>\funcdef{\ell}{\words{\Sigma}}{\N}</m> represent the length function,
		using alphabet is <m>\Sigma = \{\alpha,\omega\}</m>.
	</p></introduction>
	<task><p> Compute <m>\ell\bbrac{\funcinvimg{\ell}{B}}</m> for <m>B = \{1,10,100\}</m>. </p></task>
	<task><p>
		How many elements are there in <m>\inv{\ell}\bbrac{\ell(A)}</m> for
		<m>A = \{\alpha\alpha, \alpha\omega, \omega\omega\alpha\omega \}</m>?
	</p></task>
</activity>

<activity>
	<introduction><p>
		Suppose <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> is a function, and <m>B_1,B_2</m> are subsets of <m>B</m>.
	</p></introduction>
	<task>
		<p>
		Draw a Venn diagram illustrating that
		<md> \funcinvimg{f}{B_1 \intersection B_2} = \funcinvimg{f}{B_1} \intersection \funcinvimg{f}{B_2} </md>.
		</p><p>
		Include all of the sets
		<md alignment="gather">
			<mrow>
				A, \;\; B, \;\; B_1, \;\; B_2, \;\;
				B_1 \intersection B_2, \;\; \funcinvimg{f}{B_1}, \;\;
				\funcinvimg{f}{B_2},
			</mrow><mrow>
				\funcinvimg{f}{B_1} \intersection \funcinvimg{f}{B_2}, \;\;
				\text{ and } \;\; \funcinvimg{f}{B_1 \intersection B_2}
			</mrow>
		</md>
		in your diagram.
		</p>
	</task>
	<task><p>
		Formally prove that <m>\funcinvimg{f}{B_1 \intersection B_2} = \funcinvimg{f}{B_1} \intersection \inv{f}{B_2}</m>,
		using the <xref ref="test-sets-equality" text="custom">Test for Set Equality</xref>.
	</p></task>
</activity>

<activity>
	<introduction>
		<p> (<em>Note:</em> The parts of this question are independent of one another.) </p>
		<p> Suppose <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> and <m>\funcdef{g}{B}{C}</m> are functions. </p>
	</introduction>
	<task><p> Argue that if <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are both surjective, then so is <m>g \funccomp f</m>. </p></task>
	<task><p> If <m>g \funccomp f</m> is surjective, must <m>g</m> be? Must <m>f</m> be? </p></task>
	<task><p> Argue that if <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are both injective, then so is <m>g \funccomp f</m>. </p></task>
	<task><p> If <m>g \funccomp f</m> is injective, must <m>g</m> be? Must <m>f</m> be? </p></task>
</activity>

</worksheet>
